Although things seem to be fine on the surface, there is a problem in the program we just wrote. To observe this problem, we must add destructors for all classes. Paste the following inline definitions of the destructors in their corresponding classes, execute the program and paste the output below.

~Animal() { cout << "~Animal() called."<<endl; }
~Cat() { cout << "~Cat() called."<<endl; }
~Dog() { cout << "~Dog() called."<<endl; }

Can you see what went wrong? When using delete to deallocate memory, only the base class destructor is called where as the derived class destructor is not called at all. Although this is fine in the example we are using here but it will create memory leaks if there are any dynamically allocated variables in any of the derived class. To avoid this we declare the base class destructor as virtual. Doing this will make sure that the derived class destructor is called even if you are using a base class pointer to call the destructor. Now change the definition of the base class destructor to make it virtual, execute the program and paste the output in the box given below. Make sure you can see the derived class destructors being called in the output.

